  "prompt": "Do flu shots really work?",
  "response": "Yes, flu shots (or influenza vaccines) do work, but their effectiveness can vary from year to year. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Effectiveness**: The effectiveness of the flu vaccine depends on several factors, including the age and health status of the person getting vaccinated, and how well the vaccine matches the circulating flu viruses. In general, the flu vaccine reduces the risk of flu illness by about 40% to 60% among the overall population when the vaccine is well-matched to the circulating viruses.\n\n2. **Annual Changes**: The flu virus changes constantly, so the vaccine is updated each year to match the circulating strains. This is why it's recommended to get a flu shot annually.\n\n3. **Protection**: Even when the vaccine doesn't completely prevent the flu, it can make the illness less severe and reduce the risk of complications, hospitalizations, and death, especially in vulnerable populations like children, the elderly, and people with chronic health conditions.\n\n4. **Community Protection**: Widespread vaccination helps to protect those who cannot get vaccinated (like infants) through herd immunity.\n\n5. **Side Effects**: The flu shot can cause minor side effects like soreness at the injection site, but serious side effects are rare.\n\nSo, while the flu shot isn't perfect, it is an important tool in reducing the impact of the flu on individuals and communities. It's recommended by health authorities like the CDC and WHO.",
